   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-05_page02.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</name>
                  <date when="1829-05-08">May 8, 1829</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4">Charles</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Unless you are better prepared for the<lb/>
               event than I believe you could be, you will<lb/>
               be very much shocked when I tell you that<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">my brother William</persName> is no more.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The physicians had endeavored to<lb/>
               prepare us - but still we hoped and<lb/>
               thought we had reason to hope from his<lb/>
               apparent amendment. - He suddenly<lb/>
               &amp; rapidly grew worse yesterday - dreadfully<lb/>
               weaker, and weaker - and about 4 o clock<lb/>
               this morning expired in <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">his mothers</persName> arms<lb/>
               - <hi rend="underline">his mother</hi> I may well call her who as<lb/>
               he said &amp; felt has been the kindest of mothers<lb/>
               to him - He appeared not to suffer at the<lb/>
               last - It was happy for him that his illness<lb/>
               was so short - his release so tranquil - But for<lb/>
               us it is terrible, - awful to think that but one<lb/>
               short month since he came home to us <choice>
                  <orig>ap-<lb/>
               parently</orig>
                  <reg>apparently</reg>
               </choice> with only a cold - &amp; now is dead<lb/>
               When "On the 7<hi rend="superscript">th.</hi> of April <add>he</add> came home <del>&amp; so</del> he said<lb/>
               "to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> E.</persName> on the 7<hi rend="superscript">th.</hi> of April - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">my sister Charlotte</persName>
               <lb/>
               "died - do not be surprised if I die on the<lb/>
               "7<hi rend="superscript">th.</hi> of May" - He died on that day - as he foretold<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-05_page03.jpg"/>

               -Never did a purer or nobler mind live in<lb/>
               this world nor one go out of it more tranquilly<lb/>
               more resigned &amp; better prepared to die -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<add>rs.</add> Edgeworth</persName> are wonderfully<lb/>
               well - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">Lucy</persName> better - A letter from<lb/>
               dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet Butler</persName> this morning continues<lb/>
               to give a good account of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeS1">Sophy Fox</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxB1">
                  <unclear>Barry</unclear>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
               I know has written <add>of</add> all at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Cloonagh_IE">Cloonagh</placeName> to you<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I enclose dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>s will<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Ever <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4">my dear Charles</persName>
               <lb/>
               Your affectionate cousin<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>Will you have the goodness to order your<lb/>
               clerk to send a copy of this will to <del>Mr <unclear>Executor</unclear>
                  </del>
                  <lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n.</hi> Beaufort</persName>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Manchester-Street-51_ENK">51 Manchester Street<lb/>
               London</placeName> And will you write a line to<lb/>
               him who is I see Executor along with<lb/>
               you - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> opened &amp; read the will<lb/>
               to this family<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>I write to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName> today - But you or <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n.</hi>
                     <lb/>
               B</persName> - will communicate to him the<lb/>
               contents of the will as I do not say a<lb/>
               word about it<lb/>
               </p>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-05_page04.jpg"/>
               <p>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> E.</persName> sends with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>'s will a <choice>
                     <orig>memo-<lb/>
               randum</orig>
                     <reg>memorandum</reg>
                  </choice> about a thousand pounds which<lb/>
               he desired to leave to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JephJ1">Johnny Jephson</persName>
                  <lb/>
               - He did not say when the principal<lb/>
               should be his therefore <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> E.</persName> could<lb/>
               not mention that in her memorandum<lb/>
                  <add>but she presumes when he comes of age</add>
                  <lb/>
               Perhaps you had better in what ever<lb/>
               may be necessary to make this <choice>
                     <orig>memo-<lb/>
               randum</orig>
                     <reg>memorandum</reg>
                  </choice> exact in that particular<lb/>
               and legal &amp; returned to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. E</persName>
                  <add>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName>
                  </add> to sign<lb/>
               - you see what the intentions are<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-05_page01.jpg"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>Miss E -</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>8 May 1829</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4">Charles Fox Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>
                     </persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Rutland Square</addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
